  "prompt": "What are some words that are the opposite of include?",
  "response": "Here are some words that are the opposite of \"include,\" with slight variations in meaning and nuance:\n\n**General Exclusion:**\n\n*   **Exclude:** This is the most direct and common antonym.\n*   **Omit:** To leave out or not include, especially intentionally.\n*   **Reject:** To refuse to accept or consider.\n*   **Eliminate:** To remove completely.\n*   **Remove:** To take something away or off.\n*   **Leave out:** A more informal way of saying \"exclude\" or \"omit.\"\n*   **Except:** To specify that something is not included. (\"All students except John went on the trip.\")\n\n**Limiting Inclusion:**\n\n*   **Restrict:** To keep something within limits; to make something smaller or fewer.\n*   **Limit:** To set a boundary or restriction.\n*   **Confine:** To keep someone or something within certain limits or boundaries.\n\n**Words Related to Separating or Removing:**\n\n*   **Extract:** To take out or remove, often with effort.\n*   **Segregate:** To separate or isolate.\n*   **Isolate:** To set apart from others.\n*   **Detach:** To separate or disconnect.\n\n**Context-Specific Opposites:**\n\nThe best word to use depends on the specific context in which \"include\" is being used. For example:\n\n*   **Contain:** (If \"include\" means \"contain\") The opposite might be **empty** or **lack**.\n*   **Embrace:** (If \"include\" means \"accept\") The opposite might be **reject**, **disavow**, or **repudiate**.\n\nWhen choosing an antonym, consider the precise shade of meaning you want to convey.\n",
